## 5. Hypotheses (all currently *planned / untested*)

| ID | Hypothesis | Tested by |
|---|---|---|
| **H1 — axis-specific commitment** | Axes commit at different t. Expected ordering: `presence / gross timing / coarse class` (early) → `fine class / material` (mid) → `multi-event binding` (late). | Commitment map (C1a). |
| **H2 — commitment ≠ readout** | Some axes are committed before cheap probes can read them; the gap separates R1 (defer) from R2 (better probe). | Commitment–readout gap (C1c). |
| **H3 — separation enables gated action** | If early axes commit and become readable before late axes, axis-gated pruning/defer is safer than scalar rejection. | Policy analysis (C3). |
| **H4 — scalar rejection insufficient** | If windows differ across axes, a DiffRS-style single-scalar criterion cannot exploit them. | Comparison vs scalar-DiffRS baseline. |
| **H5 — some errors are seed-determined** | Offscreen hallucination / generic ambience may be predictable from the initial noise; if so the fix is **reseed**, not defer. | Seed-predictability analysis (separate). |

**Expect surprises and treat them as findings**, e.g. coarse class may split into coarse-early / fine-late, or hallucination may be a seed lottery rather than a window. The data, not H1's ordering, is the result.

