## 6. Contributions

### C1 — Commitment and Readout Maps (the core)
- **C1a Commitment map** (generator-side, label-free): per-axis agreement of the **self-target** across stochastic tail-forks → `t_commit(axis)` and the surface `A(axis, t, α)`.
- **C1b Readout map** (probe-side): per-axis, per-probe prediction of the **same self-target** from `x0(t)` → `t_read(axis, probe)`.
- **C1c Commitment–readout gap**: `gap = t_read − t_commit`, attributed to R1/R2 via cross-tabulation.

### C2 — Axis Measurement & Calibration Protocol
A reproducible objective measurement per axis (the self-target), an **event-anchor** protocol, a **reliability gate** (test-retest on generated audio + a small perceptual-calibration sidecar), and explicit demotion rules. Unreliable axes are demoted, not forced.

### C3 — Axis-Gated Population Pruning (main method, post-green-light)
A cascaded best-of-N policy that prunes a candidate population only on axes whose windows have closed and whose early-action precision is high; survivors continue; later axes are evaluated at later windows; finish and rerank.

### C4 — Cheap Process-Aware Verifier (only after maps show headroom)
A small axis-conditioned verifier that approximates the useful readout signal cheaply. **Value claim:** high-frequency, low-cost, intermediate-state scoring (a frontier MLLM cannot be called every step per candidate). **Not** "beats MLLM on completed audio."

### C5 — Axis-Gated Rollback (secondary, aggressive)
Use the stochastic tail mechanism (or Restart re-noising) to repair after an axis failure is detected inside its window. Not a v1 headline; runs only if forking is stable.

